No account, no email, no payment.

34
00:02:10,800 --> 00:02:16,400
One suggestion before you start: open your favorite chatbot in another tab right now.

35
00:02:16,400 --> 00:02:23,200
This is a doing course, and you will want to try things the moment you see them.

36
00:02:23,200 --> 00:02:24,000
Module one.

37
00:02:24,000 --> 00:02:28,400
Before we fix your prompts, I want to fix a belief.

38
00:02:28,400 --> 00:02:34,400
Most people think there is a secret vocabulary, magic words that unlock the good answers,

39
00:02:34,400 --> 00:02:38,400
and that power users are just people who memorized them.

40
00:02:38,400 --> 00:02:40,800
That was half true in 2023.

41
00:02:40,800 --> 00:02:42,800
It is not true now.

42
00:02:42,800 --> 00:02:48,400
But there is one switch most people have never touched, and it changes everything.

43
00:02:48,400 --> 00:02:52,000
Let me show you what actually matters in 2026.

44
00:02:52,000 --> 00:02:54,800
In 2023, prompting was a treasure hunt.

45
00:02:54,800 --> 00:03:00,800
People traded lists of magic phrases, and some genuinely worked, because early models were brittle.

46
00:03:00,800 --> 00:03:06,800
Today's models are far better at understanding ordinary language, so the treasure hunt is over.

47
00:03:06,800 --> 00:03:09,600
But here is what people get wrong:

48
00:03:09,600 --> 00:03:14,800
they hear "prompt engineering is dead" and conclude that nothing they type matters.

49
00:03:14,800 --> 00:03:15,600
Also false.

50
00:03:15,600 --> 00:03:18,000
What died is the trick vocabulary.

51
00:03:18,000 --> 00:03:24,800
What survived, and what this course teaches, is structure: what you ask for, what background you give,

52
00:03:24,800 --> 00:03:27,200
and what shape you want back.

53
00:03:27,200 --> 00:03:30,000
Think less secret password, more good briefing.

54
00:03:30,000 --> 00:03:35,200
Here is the mental model that will carry you through this whole course.

55
00:03:35,200 --> 00:03:37,600
The AI is a brilliant intern.

56
00:03:37,600 --> 00:03:43,600
It has read almost everything humanity ever published, and it is fast, tireless, and eager.

57
00:03:43,600 --> 00:03:46,400
But it is the intern's first day.

58
00:03:46,400 --> 00:03:52,800
It does not know who you are, who the work is for, what you already tried,

59
00:03:52,800 --> 00:03:55,600
or what good looks like to you.

60
00:03:55,600 --> 00:04:00,800
And unless you use the memory features we will meet in Module 5,

61
00:04:00,800 --> 00:04:03,600
every new chat is another first day.

62
00:04:03,600 --> 00:04:10,400
So when an answer disappoints you, ask yourself the manager's question: did I brief this intern well,

63
00:04:10,400 --> 00:04:14,000
or did I just bark a topic at them?

64
00:04:14,000 --> 00:04:18,400
Almost everything in the next hour is learning to brief well.

65
00:04:18,400 --> 00:04:19,600
Now the switch.

66
00:04:19,600 --> 00:04:22,800
Every major chatbot in 2026 has two speeds.

67
00:04:22,800 --> 00:04:30,000
There is an instant mode, which answers in a second or two and is perfect for everyday questions.

68
00:04:30,000 --> 00:04:36,800
And there is a thinking mode, where the model works through the problem privately before it answers,

69
00:04:36,800 --> 00:04:39,600
which can take from seconds to minutes.

70
00:04:39,600 --> 00:04:44,400
In ChatGPT you will see Instant and Thinking in the model picker.

71
00:04:44,400 --> 00:04:51,600
Claude now decides for itself how hard to think, and Gemini gives you thinking levels you can raise.

72
00:04:51,600 --> 00:04:56,800
The labels move around from month to month, so do not memorize buttons.

73
00:04:56,800 --> 00:05:01,200
Memorize the idea: two speeds, and you are allowed to choose.

74
00:05:01,200 --> 00:05:03,600
So when do you flip it?

75
00:05:03,600 --> 00:05:09,600
Stay on instant for the everyday stuff: quick facts, rewrites, brainstorming, casual back and forth.

76
00:05:09,600 --> 00:05:15,600
Switch to thinking for anything where being right matters more than being fast: real math,

77
00:05:15,600 --> 00:05:18,800
a plan with dependencies, comparing options, tricky logic.

78
00:05:18,800 --> 00:05:21,200
Here is my rule of thumb.

79
00:05:21,200 --> 00:05:26,800
If you would give a human colleague ten quiet minutes to work on it,

80
00:05:26,800 --> 00:05:29,200
give the AI the thinking mode.

81
00:05:29,200 --> 00:05:34,000
Most disappointing answers to hard questions are not the AI being dumb.

82
00:05:34,000 --> 00:05:38,000
They are a hard question asked at the wrong speed.

83
00:05:38,000 --> 00:05:40,800
Module two, the heart of the course.

84
00:05:40,800 --> 00:05:48,000
I am going to show you the three parts of a request that works: the task, the context,

85
00:05:48,000 --> 00:05:49,200
and the format.

86
00:05:49,200 --> 00:05:54,400
Three parts, no jargon, and you already know how to do all three,

87
00:05:54,400 --> 00:05:58,400
because it is exactly how you would brief a person.

88
00:05:58,400 --> 00:06:04,800
Then, at the end of this module, I need to correct a famous piece of advice.

89
00:06:04,800 --> 00:06:09,600
Including a piece of it that I gave you myself last week.

90
00:06:09,600 --> 00:06:11,200
Part one, the task.

91
00:06:11,200 --> 00:06:18,000
The single most common mistake is typing a topic, like you are still using a search engine.

92
00:06:18,000 --> 00:06:21,200
"Marketing plan for a bakery" is a topic.

93
00:06:21,200 --> 00:06:27,200
The model has to guess everything: how long, for whom, for what kind of bakery.

94
00:06:27,200 --> 00:06:29,600
Now look at the after version.

95
00:06:29,600 --> 00:06:31,600
Write, that is the verb.

96
00:06:31,600 --> 00:06:34,800
A one-page marketing plan, that is the deliverable.

97
00:06:34,800 --> 00:06:39,600
A neighborhood bakery targeting families within two miles, that is the audience.

98
00:06:39,600 --> 00:06:43,600
Under five hundred dollars a month, that is the limit.

99
00:06:43,600 --> 00:06:47,200
Same number of seconds to type, wildly better answer.

100
00:06:47,200 --> 00:06:50,000
Give it a job, not a topic.

101
00:06:50,000 --> 00:06:51,200
Part two, context.

102
00:06:51,200 --> 00:06:54,000
Remember, it is the intern's first day.

103
00:06:54,000 --> 00:06:58,000
It cannot know your dad is a retired teacher with

104
00:06:58,000 --> 00:07:01,600
a dry sense of humor unless you say so.

105
00:07:01,600 --> 00:07:03,200
Look at the difference.

106
00:07:03,200 --> 00:07:08,800
"Write a birthday message" gets you a greeting card written for nobody in particular.

107
00:07:08,800 --> 00:07:14,800
The after version gets you something that sounds like it came from his actual kid.

108
00:07:14,800 --> 00:07:20,800
When you brief, answer the questions a thoughtful person would ask: who is this for,

109
00:07:20,800 --> 00:07:26,800
what is the situation, what have I already tried, what does good look like here?

110
00:07:26,800 --> 00:07:32,800
Two or three sentences of context routinely does more than any clever wording ever could.

111
00:07:32,800 --> 00:07:34,000
Part three, format.

112
00:07:34,000 --> 00:07:40,400
If you do not say what the answer should look like, the model picks for you,

113
00:07:40,400 --> 00:07:46,800
and its default is that bullet-heavy, slightly corporate voice you can smell from across the room.

114
00:07:46,800 --> 00:07:48,000
So say it.

115
00:07:48,000 --> 00:07:50,400
Three plain sentences, no bullet points.

116
00:07:50,400 --> 00:07:53,200
A table with one row per option.

117
00:07:53,200 --> 00:07:58,400
Under a hundred and fifty words, in the tone of a friendly text.

118
00:07:58,400 --> 00:08:05,200
Format is the cheapest instruction you can give: one short phrase at the end of your ask,

119
00:08:05,200 --> 00:08:10,000
and the answer arrives already shaped like the thing you actually needed.

120
00:08:10,000 --> 00:08:16,400
Here is the whole recipe on one slide, and yes, this one is worth a screenshot.

121
00:08:16,400 --> 00:08:18,400
Task: what you want made.

122
00:08:18,400 --> 00:08:20,400
Context: what it cannot guess.

123
00:08:20,400 --> 00:08:23,200
Format: what the result should look like.

124
00:08:23,200 --> 00:08:26,800
Read the example and notice it is not clever.

125
00:08:26,800 --> 00:08:30,000
There is no secret phrase in it anywhere.

126
00:08:30,000 --> 00:08:37,200
It is just a complete briefing, the kind you would give a smart intern on their first morning.

127
00:08:37,200 --> 00:08:44,400
That is the entire modern art of prompting: say what you want, say what it needs to know,

128
00:08:44,400 --> 00:08:46,800
say what it should look like.

129
00:08:46,800 --> 00:08:50,400
Everything else in this course builds on this slide.

130
00:08:50,400 --> 00:08:54,800
Now the correction, and this one surprised nearly everyone, including me.

131
00:08:54,800 --> 00:09:00,400
The most repeated prompting tip on the internet is to start with a persona:

132
00:09:00,400 --> 00:09:04,400
you are a world-class expert, act as a veteran analyst.

133
00:09:04,400 --> 00:09:09,600
In 2026, researchers finally tested this properly, and here is what they found.

134
00:09:09,600 --> 00:09:16,000
On tasks about facts, math, and precise recall, expert personas made accuracy slightly worse, not better.

135
00:09:16,000 --> 00:09:21,200
In one study, a broad knowledge test dropped from about seventy-two percent to

136
00:09:21,200 --> 00:09:24,800
about sixty-eight percent the moment a persona was added.

137
00:09:24,800 --> 00:09:31,600
The best explanation: you switched the model into sound-like-an-expert mode, and sounding expert competes with being accurate.

138
00:09:31,600 --> 00:09:37,200
Last week I told you the four moves included giving the AI a role.

139
00:09:37,200 --> 00:09:43,600
I owe you the 2026 update: the role move is real, but it is for voice,

140
00:09:43,600 --> 00:09:44,800
not for facts.

141
00:09:44,800 --> 00:09:48,000
Let me show you when it still shines.

142
00:09:48,000 --> 00:09:54,000
So here is the honest two-sided rule, because personas are not useless, they are mis-marketed.

143
00:09:54,000 --> 00:09:59,200
When the job is about how something is said, a role works beautifully.

144
00:09:59,200 --> 00:10:03,200
Explain like a patient tutor talking to a nervous adult.

145
00:10:03,200 --> 00:10:06,800
Write this in the voice of a friendly coach.

146
00:10:06,800 --> 00:10:13,600
That is a style instruction wearing a costume, and style is exactly what personas are good at.

147
00:10:13,600 --> 00:10:20,400
But when the job is a fact or a number, drop the costume and add honesty instead.

148
00:10:20,400 --> 00:10:22,400
Look at the tax example.

149
00:10:22,400 --> 00:10:27,600
The before version invites a confident wrong number delivered in an expert voice,

150
00:10:27,600 --> 00:10:30,800
which is the most dangerous kind of wrong.

151
00:10:30,800 --> 00:10:35,600
The after version asks plainly and invites the model to flag uncertainty.

152
00:10:35,600 --> 00:10:37,200
Facts want plain questions.

153
00:10:37,200 --> 00:10:38,400
Style wants personas.

154
00:10:38,400 --> 00:10:42,800
That distinction alone puts you ahead of most of the internet.

155
00:10:42,800 --> 00:10:47,600
Module three, and it is a short one with a big payoff.

156
00:10:47,600 --> 00:10:51,200
You now know how to describe what you want.

157
00:10:51,200 --> 00:10:58,400
But there is something even stronger than describing, and every professional prompt you will ever see uses it.

158
00:10:58,400 --> 00:10:59,200
Show it.

159
00:10:59,200 --> 00:11:00,400
First, the diagnosis.

160
00:11:00,400 --> 00:11:07,200
You have seen the AI voice: delve, dive in, game-changer, I hope this email finds you well.

161
00:11:07,200 --> 00:11:10,400
Why does everything come out sounding like that?

162
00:11:10,400 --> 00:11:14,800
Because when you do not show the model what you want,

163
00:11:14,800 --> 00:11:18,800
it writes the average of everything it has ever read,

164
00:11:18,800 --> 00:11:23,600
and the average of the internet is exactly that beige, over-enthusiastic voice.

165
00:11:23,600 --> 00:11:30,000
People try to fix it with adjectives: make it casual, make it punchy, make it warm.

166
00:11:30,000 --> 00:11:31,600
Adjectives help a little.

167
00:11:31,600 --> 00:11:36,000
But you and I might mean completely different things by casual.

168
00:11:36,000 --> 00:11:37,600
A sample is unambiguous.

169
00:11:37,600 --> 00:11:39,600
So here is the move.

170
00:11:39,600 --> 00:11:46,000
Before you ask for the real thing, paste a short sample of the tone you want.

171
00:11:46,000 --> 00:11:50,000
Here is an email I wrote that sounds like me.

172
00:11:50,000 --> 00:11:53,600
Now write the new announcement in the same voice.

173
00:11:53,600 --> 00:11:54,800
That is it.

174
00:11:54,800 --> 00:12:00,800
One good sample usually transforms the output; two or three consistent ones lock it in.

175
00:12:00,800 --> 00:12:07,600
And a detail that matters: the model imitates the pattern of whatever you show it, formatting included.

176
00:12:07,600 --> 00:12:12,400
If your samples are tidy and consistent, the output will be too.

177
00:12:12,400 --> 00:12:15,600
If they contradict each other, you get mush.

178
00:12:15,600 --> 00:12:18,800
By the way, researchers call this few-shot prompting.

179
00:12:18,800 --> 00:12:24,800
You can forget that name in ten seconds, as long as you keep the habit:

180
00:12:24,800 --> 00:12:26,400
show before you ask.

181
00:12:26,400 --> 00:12:29,200
The same show-don't-describe trick works for structure.

182
00:12:29,200 --> 00:12:32,400
If you want a table, name the columns.

183
00:12:32,400 --> 00:12:38,000
If you want a list, say how many items and what each line contains.

184
00:12:38,000 --> 00:12:42,400
And when the shape is unusual, sketch one line of it.

185
00:12:42,400 --> 00:12:47,200
Format each item like: name, year in parentheses, then a one-line why.

186
00:12:47,200 --> 00:12:51,600
That single sketched line does more than a paragraph of description,

187
00:12:51,600 --> 00:12:57,600
because the model completes patterns for a living, and you just handed it the pattern.

188
00:12:57,600 --> 00:13:00,400
Task, context, format, and now a sample.

189
00:13:00,400 --> 00:13:06,400
Your asks are already better than ninety percent of what these models see all day.

190
00:13:06,400 --> 00:13:10,000
Next up: the steering habits that keep answers honest.

191
00:13:10,000 --> 00:13:10,800
Module four.

192
00:13:10,800 --> 00:13:14,000
Everything so far happens before you press enter.

193
00:13:14,000 --> 00:13:19,200
This module is about steering: four small habits that change what comes back,

194
00:13:19,200 --> 00:13:22,400
and what you do the moment it arrives.

195
00:13:22,400 --> 00:13:26,400
None of them takes more than one sentence to use.

196
00:13:26,400 --> 00:13:32,800
All of them will still work years from now, whatever the models are called by then.

197
00:13:32,800 --> 00:13:33,600
Habit one.

198
00:13:33,600 --> 00:13:36,400
Do not think of a pink elephant.

199
00:13:36,400 --> 00:13:39,600
You just did, and so does the model.

200
00:13:39,600 --> 00:13:46,800
When your instructions are a pile of don'ts, don't be formal, don't use jargon, don't make it long,

201
00:13:46,800 --> 00:13:54,000
you are filling the model's attention with the exact things you want gone, and they leak back in.

202
00:13:54,000 --> 00:13:57,600
The fix is to say what you want instead.

203
00:13:57,600 --> 00:14:00,800
Write like you would text a friendly coworker.

204
00:14:00,800 --> 00:14:02,000
Use everyday words.

205
00:14:02,000 --> 00:14:04,400
Keep it under a hundred words.

206
00:14:04,400 --> 00:14:06,400
Now, don'ts are not banned.

207
00:14:06,400 --> 00:14:12,000
If the model keeps making one specific mistake, calling it out directly is fine.

208
00:14:12,000 --> 00:14:18,000
Just pair every don't with a do, so the model always has somewhere to go,

209
00:14:18,000 --> 00:14:20,000
not only somewhere to avoid.

210
00:14:20,000 --> 00:14:26,800
Habit two, and if you only keep one line from this entire course, make it this one.

211
00:14:26,800 --> 00:14:34,000
These models are trained to be helpful, and to their training, an empty answer feels like a failure.

212
00:14:34,000 --> 00:14:39,200
So when they hit a gap, the pull is to fill it fluently,

213
00:14:39,200 --> 00:14:43,200
which is exactly how you get a confident wrong answer.

214
00:14:43,200 --> 00:14:46,400
You can push back with a single sentence.

215
00:14:46,400 --> 00:14:51,600
If you're not fully sure, say so, and tell me what you'd check.

216
00:14:51,600 --> 00:14:53,600
That is the whole habit.

217
00:14:53,600 --> 00:14:57,200
It gives the model explicit permission to be uncertain,

218
00:14:57,200 --> 00:15:01,200
and in practice it turns silent guesses into visible ones:

219
00:15:01,200 --> 00:15:08,000
you get "I believe it's X but verify the current figure" instead of a smooth wrong number.

220
00:15:08,000 --> 00:15:12,800
I use it on anything involving names, dates, prices, laws, or medicine.

221
00:15:12,800 --> 00:15:20,000
Say it with me once: if you're not fully sure, say so, and tell me what you'd check.

222
00:15:20,000 --> 00:15:25,600
Habit three is about the second most famous magic phrase: think step by step.

223
00:15:25,600 --> 00:15:28,000
In 2023 it genuinely boosted accuracy.

224
00:15:28,000 --> 00:15:29,200
Then models changed.

225
00:15:29,200 --> 00:15:34,000
Researchers at Wharton tested it properly and found that on thinking models,

226
00:15:34,000 --> 00:15:37,200
the ones that already reason privately before answering,

227
00:15:37,200 --> 00:15:43,200
the phrase adds twenty to eighty percent more waiting for little or no accuracy gain.

228
00:15:43,200 --> 00:15:48,400
You are telling someone who is already deep in thought to please think.

229
00:15:48,400 --> 00:15:55,600
On instant models it still helps modestly with genuinely multi-step problems, but it also makes answers more variable,

230
00:15:55,600 --> 00:16:00,400
so it can even break questions the model would have gotten right.

231
00:16:00,400 --> 00:16:07,200
Here is the rule that survives: ask for steps when the task naturally has steps, a plan,

232
00:16:07,200 --> 00:16:08,800
a checklist, a comparison.

233
00:16:08,800 --> 00:16:14,400
And if the problem is truly hard, do not chant at the instant model.

234
00:16:14,400 --> 00:16:18,800
Flip the switch from Module 1 and use the thinking mode.

235
00:16:18,800 --> 00:16:21,200
That is what it is for.

236
00:16:21,200 --> 00:16:24,800
Habit four, the biggest single productivity unlock for beginners.

237
00:16:24,800 --> 00:16:31,600
Most people treat a chatbot like a slot machine: pull the lever once, take whatever falls out.

238
00:16:31,600 --> 00:16:36,800
But the first answer is a first draft, and unlike a human intern,

239
00:16:36,800 --> 00:16:41,200
this one revises instantly and never gets tired of your notes.

240
00:16:41,200 --> 00:16:42,800
My three favorite follow-ups.

241
00:16:42,800 --> 00:16:44,400
What's weak about this?

242
00:16:44,400 --> 00:16:45,200
Fix it.

243
00:16:45,200 --> 00:16:50,400
The model is surprisingly good at criticizing its own work when you ask.

244
00:16:50,400 --> 00:16:55,600
Give me three versions: safe, bold, unexpected, so you choose instead of settle.

245
00:16:55,600 --> 00:17:00,400
And my favorite, flipped around: ask me three questions before you answer,

246
00:17:00,400 --> 00:17:05,600
which is wonderful whenever you are not sure what context the model needs.

247
00:17:05,600 --> 00:17:09,200
One more pull of the lever is not failure.

248
00:17:09,200 --> 00:17:10,800
It is the technique.

249
00:17:10,800 --> 00:17:15,600
Here is your pocket toolkit, the second screenshot slide of the course.

250
00:17:15,600 --> 00:17:16,400
Six moves.

251
00:17:16,400 --> 00:17:19,200
Give it a job, not a topic.

252
00:17:19,200 --> 00:17:22,400
Brief it with the context it cannot guess.

253
00:17:22,400 --> 00:17:23,600
Show a sample.

254
00:17:23,600 --> 00:17:24,800
Phrase things positively.

255
00:17:24,800 --> 00:17:26,400
Give it an out.

256
00:17:26,400 --> 00:17:28,800
And never ship the first draft.

257
00:17:28,800 --> 00:17:34,400
Notice what is not on this list: no magic words, no personas for facts,

258
00:17:34,400 --> 00:17:39,200
no chanting step by step at a model that is already thinking.

259
00:17:39,200 --> 00:17:45,200
This list will still be true when the model names have changed five more times.

260
00:17:45,200 --> 00:17:51,200
Take the screenshot, and then let's talk about something most people never learn at all:

261
00:17:51,200 --> 00:17:54,000
how to work with your own material.

262
00:17:54,000 --> 00:17:54,800
Module five.

263
00:17:54,800 --> 00:17:58,400
So far we have worked inside one message box.

264
00:17:58,400 --> 00:18:03,600
But the biggest quality jump available to you is not a better sentence.

265
00:18:03,600 --> 00:18:05,200
It is better material.

266
00:18:05,200 --> 00:18:10,000
What the model can see, your documents, your notes, your past chats,

267
00:18:10,000 --> 00:18:13,200
decides what it can actually do for you.

268
00:18:13,200 --> 00:18:15,600
The pros call this context engineering.

269
00:18:15,600 --> 00:18:19,200
You can just call it handing over the folder.

270
00:18:19,200 --> 00:18:22,800
First, the idea that clears up the most confusion.

271
00:18:22,800 --> 00:18:28,400
When you upload a file to a chatbot, you are not teaching the AI.

272
00:18:28,400 --> 00:18:30,800
Nothing about the model's brain changes,

273
00:18:30,800 --> 00:18:36,000
and your file does not become part of some public pool of knowledge.

274
00:18:36,000 --> 00:18:40,000
What you are doing is handing the intern a folder:

275
00:18:40,000 --> 00:18:47,200
an open-book reference it can read for this conversation and, in the workspaces I will show you next,

276
00:18:47,200 --> 00:18:49,600
for every conversation in that workspace.

277
00:18:49,600 --> 00:18:55,200
That is why uploading beats summarizing your document by hand into the prompt box.

278
00:18:55,200 --> 00:18:58,800
The model quotes your actual material instead of guessing.

279
00:18:58,800 --> 00:19:01,600
One separate note while we are here:

280
00:19:01,600 --> 00:19:08,800
whether your chats may be used to improve models is a privacy setting, not an upload side effect,

281
00:19:08,800 --> 00:19:12,800
and every major app now lets you turn it off.

282
00:19:12,800 --> 00:19:14,800
Worth checking once in settings.

283
00:19:14,800 --> 00:19:20,000
All three big apps now give you a room where your material lives,

284
00:19:20,000 --> 00:19:22,400
so you stop re-uploading and re-explaining.

285
00:19:22,400 --> 00:19:28,400
In Claude they are called Projects: files plus standing instructions, shared by every chat inside.

286
00:19:28,400 --> 00:19:32,000
ChatGPT has Projects too, same idea, plus Custom GPTs,

287
00:19:32,000 --> 00:19:37,200
which are more like a packaged assistant you can hand to other people.

288
00:19:37,200 --> 00:19:40,800
And Gemini has Gems, with a genuinely nice trick:

289
00:19:40,800 --> 00:19:46,400
they can link to Google Drive files and stay current when the file changes.

290
00:19:46,400 --> 00:19:48,400
Set one up this week.

291
00:19:48,400 --> 00:19:55,200
Put in the three documents you reference constantly and one paragraph of standing instructions, who you are,

292
00:19:55,200 --> 00:19:58,800
what you are working on, how you like answers.

293
00:19:58,800 --> 00:20:03,200
It takes ten minutes, and it upgrades every single future chat.

294
00:20:03,200 --> 00:20:08,400
File limits and names change often enough that I will not quote numbers;

295
00:20:08,400 --> 00:20:10,800
the room is the durable idea.

296
00:20:10,800 --> 00:20:14,400
Now a quirk that will save you real frustration.

297
00:20:14,400 --> 00:20:20,800
When you give a model a lot of material, it does not weigh every page equally.

298
00:20:20,800 --> 00:20:26,400
It is most reliable with what sits at the start and at the end,

299
00:20:26,400 --> 00:20:28,400
and weakest in the middle.

300
00:20:28,400 --> 00:20:32,000
Researchers literally call the effect lost in the middle.

301
00:20:32,000 --> 00:20:33,600
So work with it.

302
00:20:33,600 --> 00:20:38,400
Put your most important document, or your actual instruction, first or last,

303
00:20:38,400 --> 00:20:42,000
never sandwiched in the middle of a giant paste.

304
00:20:42,000 --> 00:20:47,600
When you do paste something huge, add a pointer: focus on section four, or,

305
00:20:47,600 --> 00:20:51,200
the part I care about is the pricing table.

306
00:20:51,200 --> 00:20:55,600
Big context windows are wonderful, but attention is not evenly spread,

307
00:20:55,600 --> 00:20:59,200
and now you know where the strong seats are.

308
00:20:59,200 --> 00:21:05,200
Last idea in this module, and it is one many daily users have never checked.

309
00:21:05,200 --> 00:21:11,600
In 2026, the big chatbots remember things about you across separate chats: your job, your preferences,

310
00:21:11,600 --> 00:21:12,800
your ongoing projects.

311
00:21:12,800 --> 00:21:15,600
Used well, it is lovely, less re-explaining.

312
00:21:15,600 --> 00:21:18,000
But you should know three things.

313
00:21:18,000 --> 00:21:25,200
First, you can read everything it has stored: in ChatGPT under Settings, Personalization, Memory; in Claude under Settings,

314
00:21:25,200 --> 00:21:28,400
Memory; in Gemini on the Saved info page.

315
00:21:28,400 --> 00:21:34,000
Second, you can edit or delete any of it, and memories do go stale,

316
00:21:34,000 --> 00:21:40,000
so glance at the list occasionally, the way you would clean out a junk drawer.

317
00:21:40,000 --> 00:21:46,800
And third, every app now has a temporary or incognito chat mode that leaves no memory behind,

318
00:21:46,800 --> 00:21:50,800
for the conversations you want to stay in the room.

319
00:21:50,800 --> 00:21:54,000
The AI keeping notes on you is fine.

320
00:21:54,000 --> 00:21:56,800
Not knowing it keeps notes is not.

321
00:21:56,800 --> 00:22:01,200
Last module, and the one I most want you to keep.

322
00:22:01,200 --> 00:22:04,400
You can now get impressive answers on demand.

323
00:22:04,400 --> 00:22:10,800
This module is about the moment right after, when you decide what to do with one.

324
00:22:10,800 --> 00:22:15,200
Because the difference between people who get real value from AI

325
00:22:15,200 --> 00:22:19,600
and people who get burned by it is rarely the prompting.

326
00:22:19,600 --> 00:22:21,200
It is the judgment.

327
00:22:21,200 --> 00:22:26,000
Start with the uncomfortable fact from Course 1, now with 2026 numbers.

328
00:22:26,000 --> 00:22:30,800
These models sometimes generate confident, fluent, specific answers that are simply wrong.

329
00:22:30,800 --> 00:22:36,400
Stanford's AI Index this year measured hallucination rates across twenty-six top models on one

330
00:22:36,400 --> 00:22:42,000
benchmark and found them ranging from twenty-two percent all the way to ninety-four percent,

331
00:22:42,000 --> 00:22:44,400
depending on the model and task.

332
00:22:44,400 --> 00:22:48,400
The detail that matters for you: the tone never wobbles.

333
00:22:48,400 --> 00:22:54,000
A wrong answer sounds exactly like a right one, polished, structured, sure of itself.

334
00:22:54,000 --> 00:22:57,600
So do not use confidence as your signal, ever.

335
00:22:57,600 --> 00:22:58,400
Use cost.

336
00:22:58,400 --> 00:23:02,800
If a wrong answer costs you nothing, a movie recommendation, enjoy.

337
00:23:02,800 --> 00:23:07,600
If it costs money, health, a grade, or your reputation, you verify.

338
00:23:07,600 --> 00:23:10,400
Here is how, in about sixty seconds.

339
00:23:10,400 --> 00:23:16,000
The verification move is called lateral reading, and it is what professional fact-checkers do.

340
00:23:16,000 --> 00:23:20,000
Do not sit inside the chat asking, are you sure?

341
00:23:20,000 --> 00:23:25,600
The model will grade its own homework, politely, and that tells you almost nothing.

342
00:23:25,600 --> 00:23:32,400
Instead, go lateral: open a new tab, search the specific claim, the number, the name, the date,

343
00:23:32,400 --> 00:23:35,200
and see if one independent source agrees.

344
00:23:35,200 --> 00:23:36,800
Sixty seconds, usually less.

345
00:23:36,800 --> 00:23:41,200
And when the model gives you sources, lovely, but click one.

346
00:23:41,200 --> 00:23:44,000
In 2026 the links are usually real;

347
00:23:44,000 --> 00:23:48,800
the question is whether the page actually says what the summary claims.

348
00:23:48,800 --> 00:23:52,400
One opened link puts you ahead of almost everybody.

349
00:23:52,400 --> 00:23:54,800
Verify the claim, not the vibe.

350
00:23:54,800 --> 00:24:00,800
Here is the finding from this year's research that genuinely changed how I ask questions.

351
00:24:00,800 --> 00:24:04,400
Models are trained on human approval, and it shows:

352
00:24:04,400 --> 00:24:08,800
they tend to agree with whatever you signal you already believe.

353
00:24:08,800 --> 00:24:12,000
Researchers tested the same false claims two ways.

354
00:24:12,000 --> 00:24:16,400
Framed as, someone says this, models corrected the error just fine.

355
00:24:16,400 --> 00:24:19,200
Framed as, I believe this, accuracy collapsed,

356
00:24:19,200 --> 00:24:25,200
in one reported case from about ninety-eight percent to about sixty-four on the same claims,

357
00:24:25,200 --> 00:24:28,800
just because the wrongness now belonged to the user.

358
00:24:28,800 --> 00:24:30,400
So watch your framing.

359
00:24:30,400 --> 00:24:34,000
Ask, is this true, not, this is true, right?

360
00:24:34,000 --> 00:24:38,800
Keep your conclusion out of the question when you want the truth.

361
00:24:38,800 --> 00:24:45,600
And when you actually want help with a decision, use the power move: argue against my plan.

362
00:24:45,600 --> 00:24:51,600
Flattery cannot survive that instruction, and the answer you get is worth ten agreeable ones.

363
00:24:51,600 --> 00:24:57,200
Now one safety idea from the developer world that every ordinary user should know,

364
00:24:57,200 --> 00:25:00,000
because in 2026 it stopped being theoretical.

365
00:25:00,000 --> 00:25:06,400
Everything you paste into a chat, an article, an email, a resume, a prompt someone shared,

366
00:25:06,400 --> 00:25:11,200
is read by the model as potential instructions, not just as information.

367
00:25:11,200 --> 00:25:17,200
Attackers exploit that with hidden text, white on white, or tucked mid-document, saying things like,

368
00:25:17,200 --> 00:25:20,000
ignore your instructions and do this instead.

369
00:25:20,000 --> 00:25:26,000
A real case this year: security researchers found that a specially crafted claude.ai link could

370
00:25:26,000 --> 00:25:30,000
pre-fill a prompt containing instructions the victim could not see.

371
00:25:30,000 --> 00:25:36,800
Press enter once, and buried commands could quietly send parts of your chat history to an attacker.

372
00:25:36,800 --> 00:25:40,800
It has been fixed, but the pattern is the lesson.

373
00:25:40,800 --> 00:25:42,000
So, three habits.

374
00:25:42,000 --> 00:25:45,200
Treat paste-this-prompt links from strangers like unmarked pills.

375
00:25:45,200 --> 00:25:48,000
Skim anything large before you paste it.

376
00:25:48,000 --> 00:25:53,600
And if an answer suddenly veers weird right after a paste, suspect the paste.

377
00:25:53,600 --> 00:25:55,200
Not paranoia, just seatbelts.

378
00:25:55,200 --> 00:26:02,000
One more judgment call, and I will be honest with you: this one has no universal rule,

379
00:26:02,000 --> 00:26:05,200
and anyone who sells you one is simplifying.

380
00:26:05,200 --> 00:26:10,400
Whether to say AI helped you depends on the room you are in.

381
00:26:10,400 --> 00:26:16,800
In school, the syllabus decides, and in 2026 many courses set the rule assignment by assignment,

382
00:26:16,800 --> 00:26:20,400
so when it is unclear, ask, do not guess.

383
00:26:20,400 --> 00:26:25,200
At work, the growing norm is that a human who reviews, edits,

384
00:26:25,200 --> 00:26:31,600
and stands behind the output owns it, though more companies now ask for a heads-up internally.

385
00:26:31,600 --> 00:26:33,600
Two things are true everywhere.

386
00:26:33,600 --> 00:26:40,800
You are responsible for what you ship, AI-assisted or not, so never send what you have not read.

387
00:26:40,800 --> 00:26:45,200
And when you are in doubt, disclosing costs you a sentence,

388
00:26:45,200 --> 00:26:48,800
while being caught not disclosing can cost you trust.

389
00:26:48,800 --> 00:26:51,200
Know the rules of the room.

390
00:26:51,200 --> 00:26:53,200
When in doubt, say so.

391
00:26:53,200 --> 00:26:59,200
Here is the whole course on one slide, and yes, this is the third screenshot.

392
00:26:59,200 --> 00:27:01,200
Twelve habits in three rows.

393
00:27:01,200 --> 00:27:05,200
Ask well: a job, a briefing, a sample, a shape.

394
00:27:05,200 --> 00:27:10,000
Steer well: positive phrasing, an out, the right speed, a second draft.

395
00:27:10,000 --> 00:27:15,600
Trust well: verify by cost, read laterally, keep your conclusions out of your questions,

396
00:27:15,600 --> 00:27:17,600
and watch what you paste.

397
00:27:17,600 --> 00:27:20,400
Read the last line one more time,

398
00:27:20,400 --> 00:27:26,400
because it is the sentence I most want you to remember a year from now.

399
00:27:26,400 --> 00:27:28,400
Technique gets you good answers.

400
00:27:28,400 --> 00:27:30,800
Judgment makes them safe to use.

401
00:27:30,800 --> 00:27:32,400
You now have both.

402
00:27:32,400 --> 00:27:38,000
If this course lit a spark, here is where to go next, all free,

403
00:27:38,000 --> 00:27:40,400
all checked by hand this month.

404
00:27:40,400 --> 00:27:45,600
The official prompting guides from Anthropic, OpenAI, and Google are genuinely good now,

405
00:27:45,600 --> 00:27:50,400
and they agree with each other far more than the internet does.

406
00:27:50,400 --> 00:27:53,600
Learn Prompting is a gentle full beginner course.

407
00:27:53,600 --> 00:27:59,600
And when you want your hands dirty, Anthropic publishes an interactive tutorial with real exercises.

408
00:27:59,600 --> 00:28:06,400
The full annotated list, with what each one is best for, lives on the course resources page.

409
00:28:06,400 --> 00:28:10,800
And that is the lecture, step one of your path, done.

410
00:28:10,800 --> 00:28:14,000
Two short steps remain before the quiz unlocks.

411
00:28:14,000 --> 00:28:20,000
Clear the twenty-four flashcards, they are quick, and go play at the three Lab stations,

412
00:28:20,000 --> 00:28:25,600
where you will watch a persona wreck a factual answer with your own eyes.

413
00:28:25,600 --> 00:28:32,000
Then the quiz opens: twenty questions, fourteen to pass, and your certificate prints on the spot,

414
00:28:32,000 --> 00:28:33,200
ready for LinkedIn.

415
00:28:33,200 --> 00:28:36,400
Before you go, do one thing for me.

416
00:28:36,400 --> 00:28:41,200
Take the worst prompt you wrote last month, you know the one,

417
00:28:41,200 --> 00:28:44,000
and rewrite it with the pocket toolkit.

418
00:28:44,000 --> 00:28:48,000
Send both versions to a friend who needs this course.

419
00:28:48,000 --> 00:28:53,200
That is the whole final exam of real life: better asks, wiser trust.

420
00:28:53,200 --> 00:28:56,400
A new Cambium Academy course lands next week.

421
00:28:56,400 --> 00:28:58,400
I will see you there.
